title: For Sale/Trade:  1937 Mosin Nagant Shiny Bore Proven Accurate Sealed Can of Ammo 7.62x54R
location: Rocky Mount, North Carolina, United States
postcontent:
You are welcome to meet me and shoot this rifle.  For sale or trade for equal value older 22lr or maybe other old milsurp rifle.

 More photos here: http://www.gunbroker.com/Auction/ViewItem.aspx?Item=512251696

1937 Izkevsk 91/30 7.62x54R with bayonet. Accurate, good clean proud engraving, numbers matching, early squared stock tip, magazine not lined through, buttplate not lined through, very good bore, not counterbored, strong rifling, shiny and smooth bolt, smooth trigger, earlier screwed in escusions, pre-war mfg, no comsmoline. Do not expect perfection...this a mil surplus rifle. This one shoots 2 inches with sorted/weighed silvertip surplus, it shoots under 1 inch with Russian 182 grain match, and surprisingly, under 1 inch with the old 1940's Russian lead core ammo. It shoots 1 inch with my hand loads. It shoots point of aim at 100 yards....exactly with the 182 grain and handloads, and close to POA with the silvertip. I went on a mission to find a very accurate mosin...and I did...after trying 20 plus rifles I found one that shoots 1/2 inch groups....I am keeping that one as well as the hex receiver rifles...this rifle is the runner up on accuracy but is a round receiver.   My goal was to embarrass the youngsters next to me with their modern $5000 tactacool rifles....it has been fun. This rifle is a good one with MUCH better than average mosin accuracy....PROVEN an accurate mosin....much more accurate than the "sniper" Mosins I shot against.   A word about russinan snipers......they are mostly fake snipers......even the rifles that were rejected as snipers, or drilled for a sniper scope mount and never used as such are sold as snipers.  Do you really think the russian sources are not drilling and plugging the receivers so they can get a higher price.    Rifle $250. George Kellgren, an Engineer from Sweden, moved to the US in 1979, and eventually founded the firearms company Grendel, Inc. in 1987. title: For Sale:  BERETTA model 1934
postcontent: This is a beautiful nickel finish and black ivory beretta grips. Comes with one magazine and no box. Stamped 1957 with 2 import marks and no pitting on the finish. Picture is for reference only and not actual photo of this firearm. The Beretta Model 1934 is a compact, semi-automatic pistol which was issued as a standard service firearm to the Italian armed forces beginning in 1934. It is chambered for the 9 mm Corto, more commonly known as the .380 ACP.Armi Beretta SpA of Gardone Val Trompia has a history in firearms manufacturing reaching back to 1526, when they were established as a maker of barrels. But it was not until 1915 that, responding to the needs of the military during World War I, they produced their first pistol, the model 1915. Beretta has become one of the world's largest pistol makers and the model 1934 (M1934) was their most numerous product in the pre-World War II era.It was designed and purpose-built for the Italian armed forces. In the early 1930s, the Italian army was impressed by the Walther PP pistol. Beretta did not want to lose a big military contract to their German competitor and designed the M1934 for the Italian Army which accepted it in 1937. This model was followed by the M1935, which was similar to the M1934 in most respects, except that it fired a .32 ACP (7.65 mm Browning) cartridge.Pistols made during the Fascist Era are marked with their year of manufacture in two forms: the conventional Julian date in Arabic numerals and the date in the Fascist Era in Roman numerals. The Fascist calendar commenced on 28 October 1922, so a pistol from 1937 may carry either "XV" or "XVI" as its Fascist year. Pistols taken by the armed forces usually exhibit acceptance marks stamped into the frame on the left just above the grip: "RE" (Regio Esercito) for the army, "RM" (Regia Marina) for the navy, or "RA" (Regia Aeronautica) for the Air Force, always in the form of an Eagle wearing a Royal Crown for the Royal air force. Police pistols may be marked "PS" (Pubblica Sicurezza). The Romanian military, at the time an Axis power, also purchased model 1934 (and 1935) pistols. The calibre marking appears as 9 mm Scurt (short in Romanian) rather than 9 mm Corto.[1] Romanian Army M1934's differ from Italian M1934's in that the Romanian pistols use the Russian sight picture, where the Italian pistols use the standard sight picture used by Western armies.An M1934, serial number 606824, was used by Nathuram Godse in the 1948 assassination of Mahatma Gandhi. The pistol, manufactured in 1934, was carried by an officer during Italy's invasion of Abyssinia and subsequently taken by a British officer as a war trophy. It is not known how it came to India, but Godse was given the unlicensed firearm by a co-conspirator

Butt and Forestock are checkered, this is the "Deluxe Border" model in .38/.357 Magnum and the 20" octagon barrel with adjustable front and rear sights and case hardening.
Winchester’s 1873 rifle was the “Rifle that Won the West.” It is chambered in the economical .38/.357 Magnum cartridge. A cowboy could have both a lever-action rifle and his six shooter, and needed only one cartridge belt for both. Most Texas Rangers and every old West cowboy worth his salt carried 1873 rifles. Chappo, the son of Apache war chief Geronimo, packed an 1873. And Buffalo Bill carried an 1873 lever-action rifle along with a pair of .44-40 Colts in 1876 when he worked as an Army scout. This piece of rifle history is available in a variety of distinctive models including this Special Cimarron branded Deluxe Short rifle. Don't let that fool you though, it has a 10+1 capacity and power to spare.

postcontent:
Metro Arms 1911 Bobcut is a commander sized 1911, this one us full stainless with factory wood grips. Feels and shoot great! Very accurate, I have managed to get a 1/2 or so sized hole from a full magazine at about 7 yards (yes, that was a very good day for me). The gun is easily more accurate than you or I am. The trigger has a very short amount of take up, but a very light clean break. I managed to get any of the "grit" out of it by breaking the trigger in a touch. It's a great trigger, not top competition level, but very respectable. 

Only one or two very light blemishes in the finish, really will only see them if you angle it in the light. 

Reliability has been good if you keep it happy with lube. As with any 1911. 

The amount of movement between the frame and stide or bushing and barrel is pretty much non existent. They made this gun with very tight tolerances. 

Only reason I will sell is if I get a good offer, I am on absolutely no rush to sell or to get rid of it. I love the gun, just looking to try something new.

title: For Sale:  Walther PPK/S Talo limited edition - One of only 200 available!
postcontent: This particular firearm is number 064 of 200 and is a beauty!German engraver, Gustav Ernst published a series of pattern books between 1839 and 1853. Many of the now well known early American engravers like Nimschke studied Ernst's patterns while in industrial school in Germany. This style became the foundation of American firearms engraving when his students emigrated to this country.The Walther Ernst PPK/S uses a more Germanic style Ernst pattern on the slide with a centered gold deer on a stainless pistol. The safety reflects the pattern. These were the last 200 Walther PPK/S made under contract by the S&W Houlton, Maine factory. The grips are a walnut laminate with the Walther logo and a reflection of the slide design in the center. The guns are marked sequentially "One of 200" on the frame.

title: For Sale:  Chinese AK-47 Spiker Polytech Norinco
postcontent: For Sale I have a Chinese Spiker AK-47. These are fairly rare variants of the AK with the Spike Bayonet. This is one of the guns that sat in customs and languished for years because they were on their way over here when importation from China was banned. They were finally released and had to have their Chinese Receivers destroyed and rebuilt on USA made B-West Receivers. This has all Chinese Polytech parts minus the receiver. It has the highly polished stainless steel bolt and carried as well as the highly polished blued receiver. The action is smooth as butter and overall this is the nicest looking and smoothest firing AK I've ever had the pleasure of owning. I had the B-West receiver properly heat treated at a local smith shop at the cost of $300 just as a precaution as the word around the net is some of these B-West receivers weren't properly heat treated and since then I've put several hundred rounds through it with no signs of deformation and it's been a flat out joy to shoot and it's even nicer to look at. If you look these up you will see original Chinese Spikers bring $1500-$2000 and the Spiker assemblies and Chinese wood furniture bring $400-$500 a piece by themselves so you should find this one quite the bargin. Will come with one 30 round magazine. Will ship to your FFL anywhere in the lower 48 for an extra $30 to cover shipping. Paypal payment is preferred if shipping. Email, call, or text REDACTED

title: For Sale:  Pentel Tactical Cobra EDC belt, Med Black
postcontent:
This is a new, EDC belt by Pentel Tactical, a local company. It's a Medium and has their cobra clasp, incredible belt for edc, very stiff, holds whatever you're carrying where you want it to stay, or anything you choose to use it for. Asking $30 on a $60 price tag.

text REDACTED

Blurb from Pentel -

USA Made 

Tactical Cobra EDC (Every Day Carry) Belt

Size: Med (31-38") Based on pant waist size, not true waist size

A 1.5 inch belt featuring a 1" Cobra Buckle. The 1.5 inch width fits through standard pant loops of all manufacturers.

Color: Black

The Pantel Tactical Cobra EDC Belt uses the pinnacle of heavy duty buckles...Cobra buckles. What is so special about this buckle you might ask? Well a common problem in other belts is that the webbing strength is rated  higher than the buckle. The Cobra Buckle is rated closer to the webbing at 1500lbs. The integrated locking element  permits fast adjustment of strap length. It is both compact and strong.

The quick release functionality is intuitive and smooth in which one pushes the tabs down at the same time. If just one tab is engaged the connection will still hold and fully relock on its own once released. No need to worry about the buckle unlatching while bending at the waste or sitting in a vehicle

 All stitching is clean and uses MIL-SPEC TYPE 92 thread. These specs make the belt about 1.5" wide, which is a good width and still fits in the vast majority of military/civilian  style pant belt loops. The adjustment end is tapered for ease of use and well melted to prevent fraying.

The end result is a nice stiffness to comfort ratio belt which is great for attaching a holster or sub-load to. It's as stiff as a duty belt, but offers more rigidity than most leather belts. The quick release capability makes it great for everyday use when you just need to go to the bathroom or expose your crotch for other fun activities :) .

This belt isn't cheap by any means ( mostly due to the high cost of Cobra buckles), however those who want a premium belt will be more than pleased. Buy one and be prepared to be spoiled.

Sizing for the Pantel Tactical Cobra Riggers belt is based off industry standards, your pant waist size (not your actual waist measurement)

The Cobra Rigger's Belt is in use by members of the United States Special Operations Command (USSOCOM) and line troops around the globe.

We back our gear 100% for a lifetime
